00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:40.239
that the right packages, the right modules, the right environments are in place so that when we

00:39:40.239 --> 00:39:45.280
submit code to be executed, it executes in the manner we expect, right? If I try to load the

00:39:45.280 --> 00:39:49.600
tidyverse, but my RServe environment doesn't have the tidyverse, then I've got to go through some

00:39:49.600 --> 00:39:53.760
process to contact the admin of that environment, have them make the tidyverse available, then try

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:58.239
publishing or then try executing my code again. RStudio Connect is different in the sense that

00:39:58.239 --> 00:40:03.199
any time we publish any extension, whether it's built in Python or R, the environment is

00:40:03.199 --> 00:40:06.959
automatically recreated and managed for us on the RStudio Connect side. All that happens

00:40:06.959 --> 00:40:11.040
automatically. I can have different versions of different packages used by different extensions,

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:15.439
and it's all being managed by RStudio Connect. The other thing that I didn't highlight here,

00:40:15.439 --> 00:40:19.280
but I think it's worth calling out, is that we also have the scalability introduced by RStudio

00:40:19.280 --> 00:40:25.520
Connect. So, if I have an extension that's used in lots of workbooks, and there's lots of users on

00:40:25.520 --> 00:40:29.280
those workbooks all the time, and so that extension gets lots of traffic, RStudio Connect

00:40:29.280 --> 00:40:32.719
can spin up new processes to support the load against that traffic as needed.

