00:59:03.040 --> 00:59:09.760
and open source and meant to be, you know, like, work really well with RStudio Connect,

00:59:10.479 --> 00:59:16.800
but that's not a requirement. The things that are nice that you get with RStudio Connect is

00:59:17.760 --> 00:59:25.520
management of those API keys, so your authorization and authentication needs,

00:59:25.520 --> 00:59:35.199
and the automatic handling of requests to that evaluate endpoint that get rerouted to

00:59:35.199 --> 00:59:40.719
the actual extensions that you want to be sending your request to. So, that gets handled on the

00:59:40.719 --> 00:59:47.600
Connect side for you. If you were to host these outside of Connect, you would have to write that

00:59:47.600 --> 00:59:56.080
logic out yourself. Thank you, Kelly. Another question that had a few upvotes, too, was from

00:59:56.080 --> 01:00:02.879
Vanessa, and Vanessa asked, could you speak some to why, if an organization has R tooling

01:00:02.879 --> 01:00:07.439
and staff capabilities, they wouldn't just build visualizations in Shiny?

01:00:10.800 --> 01:00:15.919
I replied to this one, too. I said, we would love it for more people to just build

01:00:16.080 --> 01:00:24.399
visualizations in Shiny, but we know that lots of organizations have already made big

01:00:24.399 --> 01:00:33.040
investments in Tableau, and so we want to be, you know, good citizens of the analytic infrastructure

01:00:33.040 --> 01:00:40.719
marketplace and space and recognize that there have been those big investments and show how

01:00:40.719 --> 01:00:49.439
the RStudio tooling and the R and open source R and Python packages can play well in that space.

01:00:50.560 --> 01:00:56.800
So, long answer to just say, yeah, we would love for more people to just build Shiny.

01:00:58.879 --> 01:01:03.600
Thanks, Kelly. And if other people have ideas, too, or things you'd like to share,

01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:08.719
feel free to use the chat, too. I see a few people were commenting in there as well.

01:01:10.719 --> 01:01:16.479
And another question, Kelly, is still new to all this, but if we're working with Sparkly R,

01:01:17.439 --> 01:01:24.639
can we push to Tableau through that as well? That's a really good question. I think that, like,

01:01:24.639 --> 01:01:32.959
there's nothing preventing that from being a pattern that you explore. The things that you

01:01:32.959 --> 01:01:39.520
want to be kind of cognizant of when you're interacting with Sparkly R, as you probably

01:01:39.520 --> 01:01:48.159
are aware, is that you want to be sure that your code is not pulling down more data than

01:01:48.159 --> 01:01:57.360
you need at any given time. So, that's always a concern when you're working with big data and

01:01:57.360 --> 01:02:05.280
you're trying to pull things down into visualizations. And I think that James and

01:02:05.280 --> 01:02:10.399
Edgar are really great people to start building out some examples of what that might look like

01:02:11.120 --> 01:02:16.639
on the RStudio side. So, I would definitely reach out on the community page about that,

01:02:16.639 --> 01:02:22.080
specifically if you have any tactical questions around how to get started.

01:02:24.959 --> 01:02:30.479
Awesome. Is there a limit to how many analytics extensions can be used

01:02:31.120 --> 01:02:35.040
on Tableau's server site? Would this work for only one extension?

01:02:36.719 --> 01:02:44.479
Yeah. So, Tableau's server sites have recently lifted the restriction around a single extension.

01:02:45.600 --> 01:02:55.199
I think when I answered this, I interpreted it from, like, the Connect perspective. On the Connect

01:02:55.199 --> 01:03:02.719
side, you can publish as many of these Plumber, Tableau, and FastAPI Tableau extensions as you

01:03:02.719 --> 01:03:09.439
want. And they get routed from requests coming through the evaluate endpoint once you've set

01:03:09.439 --> 01:03:16.800
them up to work with Tableau. So, there's sort of an unlimited set on the Connect side. And

01:03:17.840 --> 01:03:24.719
I believe the restrictions from the Tableau side for the number of extensions you can register

01:03:24.719 --> 01:03:32.879
has also been lifted per site. But definitely check on the Tableau, or I defer to the Tableau

01:03:32.879 --> 01:03:42.639
documentation on that. Great. Thank you. I saw you also shared documentation for this question

01:03:42.639 --> 01:03:50.320
in the chat, which was, does this work with Tableau's server also? Yes. And we have integration

01:03:50.320 --> 01:03:58.000
docs on our docs.rstudio.com site. So, works with Tableau server, Tableau online, and Tableau

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:05.760
desktop. Essentially should work anywhere Tableau allows Tableau analytic extensions to function.

01:04:06.800 --> 01:04:16.479
Those are the three places we know of. Thank you. I'm not sure if this question was answered in

01:04:16.560 --> 01:04:23.199
another way earlier by James, but Jay asks, can you elaborate on how authentication works

01:04:23.199 --> 01:04:30.320
between Tableau and Connect? Yeah, hopefully what James demoed right before he hopped off was

01:04:30.320 --> 01:04:37.439
an answer for that. But yeah, like at a high level, you have to set up an API key, hopefully

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:45.600
that represents a service account user on the Connect side. And then you register that as an

01:04:45.600 --> 01:04:53.520
admin on the Tableau site. And the instructions for doing all that are at that same docs page

01:04:54.080 --> 01:05:01.520
that I just said that we just linked. Great. Thank you. And Kelly, let me know if you have

01:05:01.520 --> 01:05:06.959
to run to a meeting. I'm just firing these questions. I probably have to hop off in a

01:05:06.959 --> 01:05:13.280
couple of minutes. Yeah. Okay. We'll take two more then. There was an anonymous question that

01:05:13.280 --> 01:05:19.760
said with RServe, I've been unable to publish Tableau dashboards that were using R in a server

01:05:19.760 --> 01:05:24.080
that hosted Tableau dashboards. Does the Plumber package address that?

01:05:26.239 --> 01:05:34.239
Yeah, if you can use Tableau analytic extensions and serve Plumber Tableau or FastAPI Tableau,

01:05:34.239 --> 01:05:40.320
either on RStudio Connect or somewhere else, then this should be a replacement for RServe.

01:05:44.239 --> 01:05:50.719
Thank you, Kelly. And we'll take one more. I'll say two more questions here. Derek asks,

01:05:50.719 --> 01:05:57.199
what are the limitations of the API from a data perspective? How much data can be passed

01:05:57.199 --> 01:06:06.239
in return? And what are the data type restrictions? So, James would be much better suited to answer

01:06:06.719 --> 01:06:15.679
this one. There are a couple of different script definitions from the Tableau side that you have.

01:06:15.679 --> 01:06:24.000
So, you have like some restrictions there. Most of the restrictions are on the Tableau side.

01:06:24.639 --> 01:06:36.479
And from the API perspective, we've added a bunch of tools for you to turn on

01:06:38.320 --> 01:06:48.080
debug logging at various different levels so that you can see the latency and what actual data is

01:06:48.080 --> 01:06:55.120
being passed through the request. And that should be hopefully really helpful to you when

01:06:55.120 --> 01:07:01.600
you're trying to figure out whether you've overdone it. You're sending too much. And

01:07:04.560 --> 01:07:10.800
the actual, the ability of Tableau to process the data you're sending over from Connect

01:07:10.800 --> 01:07:18.239
is going to fall over. We're only able to expose what's happening from Connect's perspective,

01:07:18.239 --> 01:07:22.719
though. Tableau in many respects is kind of a black box when it comes to

01:07:23.360 --> 01:07:32.000
understanding what its limitations are. So, I would encourage you, if you have, if you run into

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:39.280
those restrictions, to reach out to the folks at Tableau and make it known that you would love to

01:07:39.280 --> 01:07:46.080
see more transparency around what its capacity is.

01:07:49.199 --> 01:07:56.159
Awesome. One last question I saw just came in was, we mentioned a limit on the data Tableau

01:07:56.159 --> 01:08:02.239
can receive with this API, but can Tableau retrieve a pin from RStudio Connect?

01:08:02.320 --> 01:08:11.280
So, Tableau, I believe the, I'm sure that what makes this problem difficult to solve from Tableau's

01:08:11.280 --> 01:08:20.160
perspective is that Tableau doesn't allow you to just reach out to, like, a regular Plumber API

01:08:20.879 --> 01:08:30.640
or, like, Python API. It doesn't make requests in that way. It sends two types of requests,

01:08:31.279 --> 01:08:36.799
whenever it's reaching out from Tableau Analytics Extensions, it's expecting to hit

01:08:36.799 --> 01:08:44.000
an info endpoint that gives some data about, like, what it's speaking to, and then the evaluate

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:53.680
endpoint. So, requesting a pin could potentially be set up through, like, that interface Tableau

01:08:54.560 --> 01:09:01.600
has for registering data sources, but going through the same route to get that pins, I don't

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:08.640
think would work, unless you have those pins available and exposed through the Analytics

01:09:08.640 --> 01:09:15.759
Extensions, and I'm not sure that the script parameter on Tableau would allow you to set that

01:09:16.319 --> 01:09:23.200
up and make that a functional data pull, but, again, James would be a better person to answer

01:09:23.200 --> 01:09:29.759
that question in more detail. Well, thank you so much, Kelly, for jumping in here and answering

01:09:29.759 --> 01:09:35.839
some of the remaining questions. I'll sync up with Lou from our team after this, as well, and

01:09:35.839 --> 01:09:42.399
we can work on putting together a blog post with the questions, as well, to share. But I just want

01:09:42.399 --> 01:09:48.560
to say thank you all for joining today. It was great to see so many of you here. And another

01:09:49.120 --> 01:09:56.160
great event will be next week with Tom Mock, who will be going through our studio-hosted eval

01:09:56.160 --> 01:10:04.000
walkthrough, if anyone's interested. I did just share a Flix dashboard I kind of made to share

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:10.560
upcoming meetups and events, in case you don't have access to meetup at work. So, if you're

01:10:10.560 --> 01:10:18.959
interested in that, you can go to Flix.org and search for meetup at work. But thank you all so much for joining. If you do ever have any other feedback or things that you'd like to see,

01:10:19.919 --> 01:10:23.040
there's a Google form in the chat, too. We'd love to hear from you all.

01:10:23.839 --> 01:10:32.640
But thank you so much for joining, and have a great rest of the day.

